DESCRIPT: This project proposes to legalize an existing third floor studio unit under Ordinance No. 43-14. As part of the legalization, the existing rear deck and stairs to the common open space of the rear yard are noted to be in the rear yard setback, the average of depth of east and west neighbors. The project proposes to reduce/modify the existing deck and stairs to the minimum depth required for the stairs to access the rear yard open space from the second floor and third floor units. The rear yard common open space will serve three total residential units. A variance is sought to allow the minimum deck and stairs to protrude approx 6'-0" into the rearyard setback, and allow a fire wall or fire protection equivalence from the side property line.

Hamilton Families is a San Francisco Bay Area nonprofit service provider to families experiencing homelessness, with programs designed to prevent homelessness, provide shelter and stability, return families to permanent housing, and support the well-being of children experiencing homelessness. Hamilton Families is in the process of purchasing the subject property as a new permanent headquarters for their nonprofit services.

The subject property is located within the Mission Street NCT zoning district, and the first and second floors of the property are currently used for limited restaurant and instructional service uses.  Hamilton Families is looking to change the limited restaurant and instructional use to a Social Service Facility use, which is defined under SF Planning Code Section 102 as "An Institutional Community Use that provides programs and/or services of a charitable or public service nature, including but not limited to arts, education, financial or housing assistance, training, and advocacy. In addition to providing their services on site, such uses may also conduct their administrative activities on site as a Principal Use."  Under Planning Code Section 754, which governs the Mission Street NCT zoning district, Institutional Uses are permitted on the first, second, and third stories of a building.

Together, the use size for the first and second floors is 8,789 square feet.  Under Planning Code Sections 754 and 121.2, use sizes exceeding 6,000 square feet and above in the Mission Street NCT zoning district require a conditional use permit. 

The Property consists of four floors.  Hamilton Families will be occupying those four floors: basement, first, second, and third floors, which make up 14,993 sq. ft. in total.  Only the first and second floor uses require a Conditional Use Authorization because of the exceedance in the use size limit.  The basement level and third floor are currently being used as office space and Hamilton Families will continue using the basement and third floor as office space.

NAMEADDR: 11 BURNETT AVE N (313 BURNETT) / 407 BURNETT ( 333 BURNET)
DESCRIPT:
The project proposes to construct two nine-unit, nine-story, approximately 30-foot-tall from grade level (approximately 39-feet-tall with rooftop equipment) residential buildings on separate adjacent lots along Burnett Avenue in the Twin Peaks neighborhood. The proposed project at 313 Burnett Avenue would provide 25,803 square feet of residential space with five two-bedroom units and four three-bedroom units including 2,343 square feet of private deck and patio space, and 555 square feet of common open space on a shared roof deck. The project at 333 Burnett Avenue would provide 21,811 square feet of residential space with seven two-bedroom units and two three-bedroom units including 2,268 square feet of private deck and patio space, and 886 square feet of common open space on a shared roof deck. Each building would provide eight on-site vehicular parking spaces including one accessible parking space (16 spaces total) in multi-level car stackers (one in each garage), and 36 Class 1 bicycle parking spaces (18 in each building) both accessed via proposed garage or building entrances on Burnett Avenue. The project would create two approximate 10-foot-wide curb cuts for access to each of the proposed garages, and install six new street trees, four Class 2 bicycle parking spaces (two in front of each building), and new sidewalk, curb, and gutter along the new building frontages on Burnett Avenue. The project would also add two accessible curb ramps located on either side of the street intersection of Burnett Avenue and Burnett Avenue North. The project would remove one significant tree from the 313 Burnett Avenue property and three trees from the 333 Burnett Avenue property.
Excavation of a total of approximately 12,176 cubic yards of material (for both lots) to a depth of about 44 feet would be required to construct the two new residential buildings. Reinforced concrete mats bearing in the existing rock is proposed as a foundation for the two new residential buildings.

DESCRIPT:
The project site at 2107 Van Ness Avenue (Block 0575/ Lot 003) is a 10,296 square foot lot located between Pacific Avenue and Broadway Street in the Mid and Lower Polk neighborhood (the "Property"). The Property is in the RC-4 zoning district, 80-D height and bulk district, Van Ness special use district, and Van Ness Corridor planning area. The site is currently improved with a 5-story mixed-use building. 

Yue Yue LLC (the "Project Sponsor") proposes to renovate the existing 5-story building back to its original use as a residential building. Specifically, it will create 30 residential units comprised of 1 studio unit, 16 1-bedroom units, and 13 2-bedroom units.  The scope of the renovation will include major upgrades to the mechanical and plumbing systems, updated egress, and exterior improvements. The Project also proposes 1,600 square feet of common open space on the roof of the building and 4,250 square feet of ground floor retail.

DESCRIPT:
Conditional Use Application request for a change of use to establish 20 parking spaces and 20 car chargers on the ground floor of the building for private parking and electric vehicle (“EV”) charging for its autonomous vehicle rideshare fleet (the “Project”). Upgrades to the building would include adding EV charging equipment and accompanying electrical gear, upgrades to the existing bathrooms and employee amenity space, the addition of a sprinkler system, and ADA upgrades. The existing curb cuts would be maintained and no substantial changes to the building exterior are proposed. 855 Geary will be an important base of operations for Cruise’s all-electric fleet as it is centrally located in the city and will minimize deadhead miles by providing rideshare vehicles a place to park and charge that is close to rider demand.

The Project requires conditional use authorization for a Private Parking Garage use and Utility Installation in order to convert the ground floor spaces to private use and install EV charging equipment for those spaces. The existing private parking on the basement and second levels would be maintained.

DESCRIPT:
The project site is a 25' x 70' rectangular lot (1,750 sq. ft.) located on the northwest corner of Bronte and Mojave streets in the Bernal Heights district. The existing vacant and dilapidated dwelling was built in 1915 and was owner-occupied at least 3 years prior to being sold to the current owner. The building is now vacant.

The proposed project would demolish the existing one-story single-family and construct an approximately 3,040 gross sq. ft., two-family dwelling using SB-9. The ground floor would consist of a one-car parking garage with two bicycle parking next to a one-bedroom unit. The 2nd floor would be the main level of the top unit, featuring the kitchen, dining, and living areas. The 3rd floor will have three bedrooms and two and a half bathrooms. There will be open space at the rear yard as well as a small private deck on the 3rd floor.

DESCRIPT:
2550 IRVING STREET IS A 100% AFFORDABLE FAMILY HOUSING RENTAL DEVELOPMENT, OF 90 UNITS IN SEVEN STORIES, EXCLUDING PARAPETS, MECHANICAL, STAIR AND ELEVATOR PENTHOUSES, WITH GROUND FLOOR RESIDENTIAL AMENITIES (COMMON LAUNDRY, COMMUNITY ROOM AND KITCHEN, RESIDENT LOUNGE, RESTROOMS) AND SUPPORT SERVICE PROGRAM OFFICES, PROPERTY MANAGEMENT OFFICES, MEP SPACES, TRASH TERMINATION ROOM, BICYCLE PARKING, AND RESIDENT PARKING UTILIZING A PUZZLE LIFT AND PIT STACKER SYSTEM.  
 
THE PROPOSED UNIT MIX INCLUDES STUDIOS, ONE-BEDROOM, TWO-BEDROOM, AND THREE-BEDROOM UNITS. AT LEAST 50% OF THE UNITS WILL BE TWO- AND THREE-BEDROOM UNITS.  OPEN SPACE IS PROVIDED WITH AN AT-GRADE COURTYARD IN THE REAR YARD, AND A ROOF DECK AND URBAN AGRICULTURE SPACE.  STREETSCAPE IMPROVEMENTS WILL INCLUDE NEW SIDEWALK LANDSCAPING, STREET TREES, AND VEHICLE CURB CUTS FOR GARAGE ENTRY AND RESIDENTIAL TRASH.  EXISTING PEDESTRIAN CURB CUTS AT CROSSWALKS TO REMAIN.
 
The project will pursue SB35 and state density bonus law AB 1763 for zoning modifications and priority processing.  Under state density bonus law AB 1763, the project seeks exceptions, concessions and waivers for the following:
- Rear Yard
- Above Grade Parking Setback
- Usable Open Space
- Active Ground Floor Uses
- Freight Loading
The existing 2-story structure and site elements (the San Francisco Police Credit Union, surface parking and landscaping) will be demolished for the new construction.

The project will have 24-car parking spaces in addition to that, the project will remove the existing 4-curbcuts of 30' each to generate 13 new on-street parking opportunities in the immediate site perimeter of Lawton Street and 42nd which will add to the overall neighborhood available parking areas.  The project will have 41 Class-1 bicycle parking (secured for overnight parking) spaces and 13 class-2 bicycle parking (publicly accessible).

DESCRIPT: Sidewalk over subbasement to be repaired for notice of violation, removal of portion of cornice & replace with matching new wood or plaster corbels.

The project is a new learning center with flexible education spaces, a chapel, dining area, and kitchen. To provide this new space, the school will demolish a portion of the north end of the campus and replace it with an addition to the existing main academic building. The area to be demolished includes a chapel, dining hall with kitchen, administrative offices, a 34-room dormitory with eight occupants, and a garage. The addition includes three stories above a basement, the height of which will match that of the existing main academic building.

The project includes a new main entrance at the connection between the existing main academic building and the proposed addition. The connection will occur at all three levels of the building to facilitate circulation between the new and existing areas.

The project will eliminate the 13 exterior parking spaces used by the school along the northern property line as well as eight garage spaces dedicated for the exclusive use of the eight Jesuits living in the dorm rooms. There will still be 86 existing parking spaces at the south end of the campus that will remain. The project will provide 150 new bike parking spaces (120 Class I and 30 Class II spaces). The existing vehicular access and service drive will remain and will continue to provide access to the west side of the campus. The driveway will, however, be moved approximately 3’ to the south. The existing loading area will remain at the north end of the campus. The trash and recycling area will be moved to the inside of the building.

The project will require a Conditional Use Authorization for the following: (1) to allow a school use within the RH-1 Zoning District, (2) to amend an existing Planned Unit Development with a rear yard modification, and (3) for the removal of dwelling units (the 34 dorm rooms) per the criteria provided in Planning Code Section 317(g)(6).

DESCRIPT: The proposed project (“Project”) includes a change of use with both interior and exterior tenant improvements to an existing, 6-story structure containing a non-residential use (office use). The Project would convert the existing, ground-floor freight loading area fronting Clementina Street, a portion of the ground-floor parking area fronting Tehama Street, and an interior ground floor space previously occupied by a retail use fronting 2nd Street into floor area for office use. In total, 9,074 square feet of Gross Floor Area is proposed for conversion from accessory freight loading, accessory parking, and retail floor areas to office use. Two existing garage doors and adjacent curb cuts would be removed, with infill façades to match the building’s existing façades along both street frontages. The Project would modify a third (existing) garage door fronting Tehama Street to accommodate 3 new service vehicle loading spaces, replacing 2 existing freight loading spaces. The Project would reduce the number of existing accessory parking spaces from 50 to 25 spaces and would add 32 Class 1 bicycle parking spaces.

DESCRIPT:
The Property is a through-lot located in Central SoMa in the CMUO zoning district with frontages on 3rd Street and Ritch Street. It is currently improved with a two-story warehouse building, which is a contributory structure to the Clyde and Crooks Warehouses Historic District, and contains 41,166 square feet of an existing data center use. The Project proposes a third-story vertical addition consisting of 16,296 square feet of office use, and the conversion of the existing data center to office use, totaling 49,990 square feet of office space. The Project would also feature 2,567 square feet of ground floor retail along the 3rd Street frontage, 10 Class-1 and 3 Class-2 bicycle spaces, bicycle showers and lockers, and 943 square feet of private open space at the third floor.

The Project will require approval of a "Small-Cap" Office Allocation (OFA) and a Certificate of Appropriateness (CoA), pursuant to Sections 321 and 1002 respectively.

DESCRIPT:
The proposed project is limited to the replacement of the three easternmost non-historic storefronts. The proposed storefronts will be built within the existing historic openings. No original fabric will be removed and the historic character of the building will be retained. The proposed storefront design will have full-height glass with vertical steel mullions that are rhythmically spaced. The storefront will also have a horizontal steel mullion at the location of a transom line and another horizontal steel mullion at the lower portion of the storefront. The panels below the lower horizontal mullion are proposed to be steel and will have the appearance of a bulkhead. The storefront will rest on the existing concrete base which is low in height.  The entry door to the restaurant seating area will be located at the second bay from the east end and will be a framed door with a glazed panel. This portion of the storefront (7’-6” in length) will be set back to prevent the door from crossing the property line as it swings out. The third bay from the eastern end of the building will have an entry door to the restaurant’s kitchen. This door will be a solid metal door with a painted metal surround. The storefront glazing in this bay will be back-painted approximately halfway up the storefront to hide back of house storage.

The proposed storefront will be compatible with the District through the use of painted steel, a material found throughout the Jackson Square Historic District. The new storefront design will also be compatible with its reference to both a bulkhead and transom line. The storefront mullions convey verticality, a characteristic that is compatible with typical punched windows in contributing buildings in the District.

DESCRIPT:
The proposed project site is located on the southwest corner of Mission and Harrington streets, on the block bound by Harrington Street to the north, Mission Street to the east, Norton Street to the south, and Alemany Boulevard to the west. The proposed project would demolish the two existing two-story commercial buildings, currently an Everything $1.50 or Less store at 4550 Mission Street and a vacant commercial space at 4570 Mission Street, previously occupied by a Payless Shoe Source, and would construct a new mixed-use residential and commercial building. 

The proposed building would include 69 dwelling units, consisting of 36 one-bedroom units, 23 two-bedroom units, and 10 three-bedroom units. The proposed building would be six stories tall and 64 feet in height to the roof (as measured from Mission Street, and approximately 79 feet in height to the top of the elevator penthouse) and would contain approximately 74,410 gross square feet. The building would contain 3,690 square feet of ground-level commercial space. Open space would be provided in private patios on the ground-level, and a common deck with an adjacent stormwater garden. Common open space decks would also be provided on the 6th floor and roof, along with solar panels. 

The project would utilize the HOME-SF program to increase the building height from 40 feet to 55 feet for the 4570 Mission Street parcel, and from 56 feet to 64 feet for the 4550 Mission Street parcel. The proposed project would add a curb cut along Harrington Street for an entrance to a ramp for a basement parking garage. The garage would contain a total of 31 vehicle parking spaces (including two ADA spaces) and 86 Class I bicycle parking spaces. Two Class II bicycle parking spaces would be provided along the Mission Street frontage. The sidewalk along Harrington Street would be expanded from approximately eight feet to 14 feet. 

The proposed construction would require excavation over an approximately 12,510 square foot area to an average depth of 15 feet for a total excavation of approximately 6,950 cubic yards of soil. A total of 10 new trees would be planted, five along Mission Street, and five along Harrington Street. The existing street tree in front of 4570 Mission Street would remain, as would the existing plaque in the sidewalk commemorating the childhood home of Jerry Garcia at the corner of Mission and Harrington streets. The building would be supported by a mat slab foundation with six inches of underlaying drain rock.

NAMEADDR: 11 BURNETT AVE N (313 BURNETT) / 407 BURNETT ( 333 BURNET)
DESCRIPT:
The project proposes to construct two nine-unit, nine-story, approximately 30-foot-tall from grade level (approximately 39-feet-tall with rooftop equipment) residential buildings on separate adjacent lots along Burnett Avenue in the Twin Peaks neighborhood. The proposed project at 313 Burnett Avenue would provide 25,803 square feet of residential space with five two-bedroom units and four three-bedroom units including 2,343 square feet of private deck and patio space, and 555 square feet of common open space on a shared roof deck. The project at 333 Burnett Avenue would provide 21,811 square feet of residential space with seven two-bedroom units and two three-bedroom units including 2,268 square feet of private deck and patio space, and 886 square feet of common open space on a shared roof deck. Each building would provide eight on-site vehicular parking spaces including one accessible parking space (16 spaces total) in multi-level car stackers (one in each garage), and 36 Class 1 bicycle parking spaces (18 in each building) both accessed via proposed garage or building entrances on Burnett Avenue. The project would create two approximate 10-foot-wide curb cuts for access to each of the proposed garages, and install six new street trees, four Class 2 bicycle parking spaces (two in front of each building), and new sidewalk, curb, and gutter along the new building frontages on Burnett Avenue. The project would also add two accessible curb ramps located on either side of the street intersection of Burnett Avenue and Burnett Avenue North. The project would remove one significant tree from the 313 Burnett Avenue property and three trees from the 333 Burnett Avenue property.
Excavation of a total of approximately 12,176 cubic yards of material (for both lots) to a depth of about 44 feet would be required to construct the two new residential buildings. Reinforced concrete mats bearing in the existing rock is proposed as a foundation for the two new residential buildings.
